{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1767"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.15,0.02,0.41,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75900"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1767"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"915"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45935"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 45-year-old woman presents with a two-day history of increasing upper abdominal pain. Over the last month, she has experienced several episodes of self-resolving right upper abdominal pain. Each episode lasted no more than 30 minutes. On examination, her temperature is 37.8C, pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 110/60mmHg. There is scleral icterus. There is tenderness to light palpation in the right upper quadrant and epigastrium. An ultrasound examination shows dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary system and a stone impacted in Hartmann\u0027s pouch. The common bile duct looks of normal diameter. Her liver function tests are shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholangitis","Acute cholecystitis","Bouveret\u0027s syndrome","Mirizzi syndrome","Choledocholithiasis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an acute inflammatory problem that has been complicated by obstructive jaundice. \u003Cstrong\u003EMirizzi\u2019s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E describes common hepatic duct obstruction which has occurred secondary to an acute inflammatory response to a gallstone impacted in either the neck of the gallbladder or the cystic duct itself. Due to the proximity of the common hepatic duct to the cystic duct, obstruction caused by large gallstones in the Hartmann\u0027s pouch lead to extrinsic mechanical compression of the common hepatic duct which leads to acute cholangitis-like features (eg, fever, right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, predominantly elevated ALP and GGT). Hartmann\u0027s pouch is a small out-pouching at the junction of the gallbladder neck and the cystic duct. The diagnosis can be confirmed with an abdominal ultrasound that reveals dilatation of the biliary system above the level of the Hartmann\u0027s pouch (ie, dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary system) and a stone in the Hartmann\u0027s pouch while the common bile duct below the level of the stone looks normal in terms of diameter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECholangitis presents with symptoms similar to Mirizzi syndrome. However, abdominal ultrasound will show distal dilatation and may even show a stone in the distal common bile duct (often difficult to see due to overlying bowel gas). This patient\u0027s ultrasound reveals a stone in the Hartmann\u0027s pouch with a normal diameter of the common bile duct and this is consistent with the diagnosis of Mirizzi syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute cholecystitis refers to the inflammation of the gallbladder caused by an impacting stone in the cystic duct. It presents with fever and right upper quadrant pain. However, jaundice and elevated liver enzymes are unlikely to be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBouveret\u0027s syndrome is an uncommon sequela of acute cholecystitis where a stone may obstruct the pylorus or the duodenum due to a cholecystoduodenal fistula. The fistula is a secondary event to the acute inflammatory process. This syndrome presents with symptoms of gastric outlet obstruction (eg, nausea, vomiting, early satiety). Liver enzymes are typically normal and jaundice is not a likely finding in Bouveret\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECholedocholithiasis is the presence of a stone or stones in the biliary tree. Often these stones will pass through the common bile duct and into the duodenum without causing any symptoms. However, they can be associated with obstruction and or sepsis. Obstruction may present as a picture of extrahepatic cholestasis, with jaundice, pale stools, dark urine. Ultrasound typically reveals a stone in the common hepatic duct. This patient\u0027s ultrasound findings make the diagnosis of choledocholithiasis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Mirizzi syndrome is an uncommon complication of acute cholecystitis."],"references":["Pemberton M, Wells AD. The Mirizzi syndrome. Postgrad Med J. 1997;73(862):487-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9307740/","Koo JGA, Tham HY, Toh EQ, et al. Mirizzi Syndrome-The Past, Present, and Future. Medicina (Kaunas). 2023;60(1):12. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10818783/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19436"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19436"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c1d9574-ddcc-4959-8df6-f7747f105de8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c1d9574-ddcc-4959-8df6-f7747f105de8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":305}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T12:59:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-25T07:47:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1767"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75900"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr